OPTION 1: OPEN SOURCE (AGPL-3.0-or-later)

If you do not hold a commercial license, your use of Earmark is governed by the GNU Affero General Public License v3.0 or later.

The full text of the AGPL-3.0 is available at:
https://www.gnu.org/licenses/agpl-3.0.html

In plain terms, the AGPL-3.0 permits you to:

  - Use, study, and modify the software without restriction.
  - Deploy the software internally within your organisation.
  - Distribute or publicly deploy the software, provided that you release the complete source code of your version under the same license.

The key obligation: if you run a modified version of Earmark as a network service (e.g., an API or web application that others access), you must make your source code available to those users under the AGPL-3.0. This applies even if you do not distribute binaries.

If you use Earmark internally without modifications and without exposing it as a service to external users, the AGPL-3.0 imposes no source-release obligation.

OPTION 2: COMMERCIAL LICENSE

If the AGPL-3.0 terms are incompatible with your intended use — for example, if you want to:

  - Include Earmark in a proprietary product or service
  - Distribute Earmark without releasing your source code
  - Offer Earmark as part of a hosted service without AGPL obligations

then you must obtain a commercial license from the project maintainers.

